–":"1283–Overleden","1280–Male":"1280–Overleden","1299–Female":"1299–Overleden","1283–Female":"1283–Overleden","1315":"1315","1299":"1299","1283":"1283","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Doncaster, , South Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1283–":"1283–Deceased","1280–Male":"1280–Deceased","1299–Female":"1299–Deceased","1283–Female":"1283–Deceased","1315":"1315","1299":"1299","1283":"1283","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Doncaster, , South Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Doncaster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Doncaster in Yorkshire, from the river name <i>Don</i> (a Celtic name meaning ‘water, river’) + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘Roman fort or walled city’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":7,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":32,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":45,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":99,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William de Doncaster was born in 1283, in Doncaster, Yorkshire, England. She married William de Doncaster in 1299, in Doncaster, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1283–":"1283–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1299–Female":"1299–Surnud","1283–Female":"1283–Surnud","1315":"1315","1299":"1299","1283":"1283","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Doncaster, , South Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1283–":"1283–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1299–Female":"1299–Kuollut","1283–Female":"1283–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1299":"1299","1283":"1283","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Doncaster, , South Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1283–":"1283–Décédée","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1299–Female":"1299–Décédée","1283–Female":"1283–Décédée","1315":"1315","1299":"1299","1283